-- Cocoa Climbs on Speculation About Crop Delays; Coffee Declines
-- B y   I s i s   A l m e i d a
-- 2013-07-03T09:56:22Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-03/cocoa-climbs-on-speculation-about-crop-delays-coffee-declines.html
Cocoa rose for a second day in London
on speculation the next harvest in West Africa, the world’s
largest-producing region, will be delayed. Coffee fell.  Weather is dry in eastern  Ivory Coast , the leading
producer, and more rain is needed in second-ranking  Ghana , MDA
Weather Services in Gaithersburg,  Maryland , said in a report e-mailed yesterday. Rain in Ivory Coast and Ghana will be light to
moderate this week, ranging from 0.25 inch to 2 inches,
according to the report. Harvesting of the main crop in Ivory
Coast and Ghana usually starts in October.  “The recent rain levels in Ghana were not as good as in
Ivory Coast,” Eric Sivry, head of agriculture options brokerage
at Marex Spectron in London, said in a report e-mailed today.
“Traders also expressed a fear that current settings may be
indicating a late start of the main crop.”  Cocoa for September delivery advanced 0.6 percent to 1,483
pounds ($2,261) a metric ton by 10:40 a.m. on NYSE Liffe in
 London . Prices rallied 1.5 percent yesterday. Cocoa for
September delivery gained 1 percent to $2,199 a ton on ICE
Futures U.S. in  New York , after gaining 0.9 percent yesterday.  Cocoa trees in eastern Ivory Coast are aging and need more
rain to produce good quantity of beans, Theodore Guetat, a
farmer in Abengourou, near the border with Ghana, said by phone
June 25. Rainfall in the region will be needed no later than
July, Leon Edoukou Adou, head of a local farmer cooperative,
said by phone on the same day.  No Rain  Ivory Coast’s central-western Daloa region, which produces
about 300,000 tons a year, got no rains from June 21-30, data
from the to the National Meteorological Service on Bloomberg
showed. That compares with a long-term average of 42 millimeters
(1.7 inches). The town of Bondoukou in the eastern part of the
country, got 10.8 millimeters, below the long-term average of 39
millimeters.  Robusta coffee for September delivery fell 1.2 percent to
$1,802 a ton in London. Arabica for delivery in September
retreated 2.5 percent to $1.212 a pound on ICE.  White sugar for October delivery dropped 0.2 percent to
$476.60 a ton on NYSE Liffe. Raw sugar for delivery in October
declined 0.1 percent to 16.51 cents a pound on ICE.  To contact the reporter on this story:
